Ask HN: Do you use any kind of journal to improve the efficiency of learning?
text:
After several years of playing around with different tools, it turns out it's easiest for me just to use Notion and its simplest features (basically creating pages).

What I have discovered recently is that it's really useful (or at least I am inclined to do that) to keep track of you daily findings or useful ideas as a developer.

An example is a pretty simple technical concept like dealing with polymorphic associaions in database modeling. There is nothing rocket sciency here, but having read a chapter in Bill Karwin's SQL Antipatterns book, I feel like I have learned a lot.

That said, it often happens that you might not encounter certain techniques or approaches for a long time and your knowledge fades.

This is why I briefly described the problem solved on my Notion journaling page, noted the book chapter and tried to summarize the approaches I considered and the one I ended up with (and why). At least, now I feel some kind of mental relief :)

What approaches do you use to make sure that your new pieces of knowledge do not evaporate too fast?

Show HN: App to Draw Silly Faces
text:
I created a free Android app (no ads, no accounts) for kids to draw silly faces.

It's easy to use: tap a brush (eye/nose, etc) and on canvas to draw.

The game element is that you can make combinations to discover more brushes. Triangle eye + mouth = tail, etc.

- Built in React Native - It contains no language, so for all languages - For all ages. - Free, no ads, no in app purchases

Created for fun, my kids like it. It has very few users, would be great to get some feedback.

(It's also a prototype for creating a mini wireframing/UX tool with comparable interace. Where you can draw boxes, buttons, etc. But what would be a seperate Show HN once it's live.)
